"/> While they aren't building any customer loyalty, I can see why they
aren't honoring them. A couple years back, I took over an existing
store after their lease ran out. I purchased all the equipment, but
changed the name of the store and the product line. Within days of
being open, I had a large number of customers attempt to redeem their
GC's from the previous store. It seems that once the employees and
managers found out the store was closing, they handed the GC's out to
anyone that made a purchase. To placate the customers that were loyal
to the previous store, I offered a discount off their purchase if they
presented the GC and ended up gaining some loyal customers.

It's not the same situation, but it's possible the previous owners
might be giving them out to friends and family since it doesn't affect
their bottom line, the restaurant has been sold.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

&gt;I was under the impression that when one bought a business, unless there was
&gt;a bankruptcy, the new owners aquired the obligations of the old owners.
&gt;This business was operating in the same location under the same name. I
&gt;spoke with the new owner and asked him if the old owners filed bankruptcy.
&gt;He indicated no--it was just an &quot;asset sale.&quot;

"/> Not necessarily. The previous owner's debts don't carry forward unless
specifically stated in the sale. And who would be crazy enough to
accept that deal? Any debt owed to vendors, IRS, etc are paid with the

proceeds of the sale, or at least should be. I would doubt that it's
illegal to refuse the GC, they should have offered at least some sort
of discount to try and rectify the situation.

