"/> The question is whether the new owners bought the _business_ or
bought the _assets_. The distinction can be crucial.

For instance, I had a CD with some bank back when interest rates
were high in the reign of George I. I was getting 10% a year for
something like five years, guaranteed. Another bank bought the
_assets_ of my bank, and unilaterally announced that they were
reducing my interest rate. I checked with the Feds and it was legal.

So in this case it's at least possible that when the OP said the new
restaurant bought the _assets_ of the old restaurant, that was
actually true. In that case the $25 paid for the gift certificate
passes to the new owners, but the obligation to service the gift
certificate (the liability) remains with the old owners. If that is
true -- and I say _if_, because we don't have all the facts, then
the OP's recourse is probably against the old owners, who will have
to refund the $25 out of the proceeds of the sale, unless of course
those proceeds have already gone to pay off other creditors.

Regardless, the OP should do what nobody (so far) has suggested:
call the consumer protection division or attorney general's office
and ask about this.

