This is a bit more on the creative thinking/crazy side, but for the
sake of argument. A person purchases the restaurant equipment, signs,
and location. The previous restaurant has existing coupons, specials,
etc. They do not change the signage or store in any way.

The problem this creates is that the store is now portraying an image
that they are in fact the same restaurant. It is very likely that
this would be done or believed to be done in order to retain the
previous business of the restaurant.

If they actively appear to be pretending to be the old restaurant it
becomes clear that they are actively attempting to deceive the public
into believing that they are in fact the old restaurant. This
therefore could possibly be argued to be a deceptive practice.

Of course, it would not be quite this simple to argue, but I think by
keeping the name and elements of the restaurant the same it creates an
opening that allows many other elements to be considered and possibly
argued as a deceptive practice.

Keep in mind that most statutes regarding deceptive practices are not
highly specific as to what creates the deceptive practice. Florida
for example, states:

Unfair methods of competition, unconscionable acts or practices, and
unfair or deceptive acts or practices in the conduct of any trade or
commerce are hereby declared unlawful.

Of course, this would not create a contract when a contract does not
exist. My previous post was not clear and was misleading when I
stated &quot;other consumer protection statute to make a case regarding
it&quot;. What I meant to say was that it may create another cause of
action. Your point regarding novation is valid and even if they were
deemed to violate a deceptive practices act they would not become
contractually obligated as they would remain two separate causes of
action.

</POST>



