"/> First, if it stays in small claims you can expect the filing fee and 1
to 2 days of court time. This is expensive in comparision of the
amount they are looking to collect. Remember the old saying time is
money. Thus your $30 judgment may cost $300, in comparision of the
amount of the judgment that is expensive.

Second, there is a fatal flaw in your arguement, it might not stay in
small claims. Many jurisdictions have methods in which you may remove
the small claims action from small claims court. Arizona for example
allows either party to request the small claims matter to be
transfered to the Justice Courts. Once that happens you are subject
to the regular rules of civil procedure.

When you consider court you have to consider that it might not result
in a legal, logical, or responsible result. It is not uncommon for a
person to counter sue you for no reason and drag the matter out in
regular court if they are allowed to do so in their jurisdictions.
Unfortunately, time missed at work, travel time, many costs and
expenses, are not covered, thus they come out of your pocket.

